136. animam: All through here by animo ‘soul’ the poet means the life-principle, through which the body feels, and through which the mind sends its directing impulse to the limbs. See n. to 94. In ani- mus and anima is the distinction, maintained also by the Stoice, between the rational and the irrational soul, the reason ancl the vital principle.
